Asynchronous programming is one of the most important JavaScript concepts for QA automation.
It is also one of the most common sources of automation bugs.
A missing await can cause:

• Tests to execute steps in the wrong order

• Assertions to run before the application is ready

• Browser actions to overlap unexpectedly

• API data to be used before it has arrived

• Tests to pass or fail unpredictably

• Unhandled Promise rejections

• Flaky automation
If you work with Playwright, WebdriverIO, API testing, database calls, or any modern JavaScript automation framework, understanding asynchronous execution is essential.
This article explains:

• Why JavaScript needs asynchronous programming

• What Promises are

• How async and await work

• Why missing await causes automation failures

• How to handle asynchronous errors

• How to build API-to-UI workflows

• How to run independent operations concurrently with Promise.all()

Why Is JavaScript Asynchronous?
JavaScript executes code on a single main execution thread.
At a basic level, this means JavaScript processes one piece of JavaScript code at a time.
But automation constantly performs operations that take time:

• Loading a web page

• Waiting for an element

• Clicking a button

• Sending an API request

• Reading a file

• Querying a database

• Waiting for a timer

• Communicating with a browser
Consider an API request that takes three seconds.
If JavaScript had to block the entire runtime while waiting for the network response, nothing else could progress during that waiting period.
Instead, JavaScript runtimes use an asynchronous architecture involving concepts such as:

• The call stack

• Host or runtime APIs

• Task queues

• Microtask queues

• The event loop
The exact runtime environment may be a browser or Node.js, but the central idea is the same:
JavaScript can start an asynchronous operation, allow the runtime to handle the waiting, and continue processing the result when it becomes available.

A Simple Synchronous Example
Consider:
console.log("Step 1");
console.log("Step 2");
console.log("Step 3");The output is predictable:
Step 1
Step 2
Step 3Each statement completes before the next one executes.
Now consider an asynchronous operation:
console.log("Step 1");setTimeout(() => {
console.log("Step 2");
}, 2000);console.log("Step 3");The output is:
Step 1
Step 3
Step 2Why?
Because setTimeout() schedules work for later.
JavaScript does not stop at that line and wait for two seconds.
The callback becomes eligible to run after the timer completes and the event loop can schedule it.
This is the foundation of asynchronous JavaScript.

The Event Loop: The High-Level Mental Model
You do not need to understand every internal runtime detail to write good automation, but you should understand the basic execution model.
Imagine this code:
console.log("Start");setTimeout(() => {
console.log("Timer completed");
}, 1000);console.log("End");The high-level flow is:

• JavaScript executes console.log("Start").

• The timer is registered with the runtime environment.

• JavaScript continues instead of blocking for one second.

• JavaScript executes console.log("End").

• The timer eventually completes.

• Its callback becomes eligible for execution.

• The event loop allows the callback to run when the call stack is available.
The output is:
Start
End
Timer completedThe key point is:
JavaScript does not need to sit idle on the call stack while an external operation is waiting to complete.
This model is fundamental to browser automation and API testing.

The Promise Model
A Promise is an object representing the eventual completion or failure of an asynchronous operation.
A useful analogy is a food-court buzzer.
You order food and immediately receive a buzzer.
The buzzer is not the food.
It represents something that will complete later.
Eventually:

• Your food becomes ready.

• Or something goes wrong with the order.
A Promise works similarly.
It represents a result that may become available in the future.

The Three States of a Promise
A Promise can exist in one of three states.
Pending
The operation is still in progress.
For example:
Waiting for API response...Fulfilled
The operation completed successfully.
The Promise produces a result.
For example:
Test Data LoadedRejected
The operation failed.
The Promise produces an error or rejection reason.
For example:
Request TimeoutOnce a Promise becomes fulfilled or rejected, it is settled.

Creating a Promise
Here is a simple example:
function fetchTestData() {
return new Promise(
(resolve, reject) => {
const success = true; if (success) {
resolve(
"Test Data Loaded"
);
} else {
reject(
new Error(
"Timeout Error"
)
);
}
}
);
}The Promise receives two functions:
resolve
rejectCall:
resolve(value)when the operation succeeds.
Call:
reject(error)when the operation fails.

Consuming a Promise with .then() and .catch()
The traditional Promise syntax uses chaining.
fetchTestData()
.then(data => {
console.log(data);
})
.catch(error => {
console.error(error);
});If the Promise is fulfilled:
.then(...)handles the result.
If the Promise is rejected:
.catch(...)handles the error.
The output in our example is:
Test Data Loadedbecause:
success = true
Promise Chaining
Promises can be chained.
fetchTestData()
.then(data => {
console.log(
"Data received:",
data
); return processTestData(data);
})
.then(processedData => {
console.log(
"Processed:",
processedData
);
})
.catch(error => {
console.error(
"Pipeline failed:",
error
);
});This works, but longer asynchronous workflows can become harder to read.
That is where async and await become useful.

The Modern Approach: async and await
async and await provide cleaner syntax for working with Promises.
They do not replace Promises.
They are built on top of the Promise model.
Instead of:
fetchTestData()
.then(data => {
console.log(data);
})
.catch(error => {
console.error(error);
});you can write:
async function loadData() {
try {
const data =
await fetchTestData(); console.log(data);
} catch (error) {
console.error(error);
}
}The code reads from top to bottom, which often makes asynchronous workflows easier to understand.

What Does async Do?
When you declare a function with:
asyncthe function always returns a Promise.
Consider:
async function getMessage() {
return "Test Complete";
}Calling:
getMessage();does not directly return:
"Test Complete"It returns a Promise that fulfills with:
"Test Complete"You can consume it using:
getMessage().then(message => {
console.log(message);
});or:
const message =
await getMessage();inside an asynchronous context.

What Does await Do?
await waits for a Promise to settle.
Consider:
const data =
await fetchTestData();If the Promise fulfills, data receives the fulfilled value.
If the Promise rejects, an error is thrown at that point and can be handled with try/catch.
The important detail is:
await pauses the surrounding async function. It does not freeze the entire JavaScript runtime.
Other work can continue in the runtime while the awaited asynchronous operation is pending.

Where Can await Be Used?
Traditionally, await is used inside an async function:
async function runTest() {
const data =
await fetchTestData();
}Modern JavaScript modules can also support top-level await in environments that allow it.
For QA automation, the most common pattern is:
test(
"user can log in",
async ({ page }) => {
await page.goto(
"https://app.com"
);
}
);The test callback is declared async, allowing browser operations to be awaited.

Why QA Automation Is Full of Asynchronous Operations
Modern automation frameworks communicate with:

• Browsers

• Browser processes

• Network services

• APIs

• File systems

• Databases

• External services
These operations do not complete instantly.
For example:
await page.goto(
"https://app.com"
);Navigation takes time.
Similarly:
await page
.getByRole(
"button",
{ name: "Login" }
)
.click();The browser interaction is asynchronous.
And:
const response =
await request.post(
"/api/login"
);requires waiting for a network response.
The automation code must coordinate these operations correctly.

The Missing await Bug
One of the most common mistakes in JavaScript automation is forgetting await.
Consider:
async function brokenTest() {
page
.getByRole(
"button",
{ name: "Login" }
)
.click(); page
.getByLabel("Username")
.fill("admin");
}Both operations return Promises.
Without await, JavaScript starts the first operation and immediately continues executing the function.
The code does not explicitly wait for the first action to complete before moving to the next statement.
This can create unexpected behavior when operations depend on one another.

The Correct Sequential Flow
Use:
async function solidTest() {
await page
.getByRole(
"button",
{ name: "Login" }
)
.click(); await page
.getByLabel("Username")
.fill("admin");
}Now the execution order is explicit.
First:
await page
.getByRole(
"button",
{ name: "Login" }
)
.click();The surrounding async function waits for the click Promise to settle.
Then:
await page
.getByLabel("Username")
.fill("admin");executes.

A More Realistic Login Example
Normally, you would fill the credentials before clicking the login button.
async function loginUser(
page,
username,
password
) {
await page
.getByLabel("Username")
.fill(username); await page
.getByLabel("Password")
.fill(password); await page
.getByRole(
"button",
{ name: "Login" }
)
.click();
}Then:
await loginUser(
page,
"admin",
"SecurePass123"
);Each dependent step completes in sequence.

await Does Not Mean Every Line Must Be Sequential
This is an important distinction.
Suppose you have three independent API requests:
const endpoints =
await fetchEndpoints();const users =
await fetchUsers();const features =
await fetchFeatures();This executes sequentially.
The flow is:
fetchEndpoints
↓
wait
↓
fetchUsers
↓
wait
↓
fetchFeatures
↓
waitIf each request takes two seconds, the total time may be roughly six seconds.
But if the operations are independent, sequential execution wastes time.
This is where Promise.all() becomes useful.

Error Handling with try/catch
When an awaited Promise rejects, JavaScript throws an error at the await expression.
You can handle it using:
try {
// Async operations
} catch (error) {
// Error handling
}Example:
async function getAuthToken(
apiUrl,
credentials
) {
try {
const response =
await mockApiCall(
apiUrl,
credentials
); return response.token;
} catch (error) {
throw new Error(
`Auth API Pipeline Failure: ${error.message}`,
{ cause: error }
);
}
}This adds context to the original failure.
Instead of receiving only:
Request failedyou may receive:
Auth API Pipeline Failure: Request failedThis makes debugging easier.

Do Not Catch Errors Just to Hide Them
This is bad:
try {
await performCriticalSetup();
} catch (error) {
console.log(
"Setup failed, continuing anyway"
);
}If the setup is required for the test, continuing may create misleading failures later.
For required preconditions, either:

• Let the original error propagate.

• Add useful context and rethrow it.
Example:
try {
await performCriticalSetup();
} catch (error) {
throw new Error(
`Critical setup failed: ${error.message}`,
{ cause: error }
);
}Good error handling should improve diagnosis, not hide defects.

End-to-End QA Scenario: API-to-UI Authentication Pipeline
A common automation pattern is:

• Authenticate through an API.

• Extract the authentication token.

• Inject authentication state into the browser.

• Open the application.

• Validate the authenticated UI.
This combines multiple asynchronous operations.

Step 1: Create the Async API Request Handler
async function getAuthToken(
request,
apiUrl,
credentials
) {
const response =
await request.post(
apiUrl,
{
data: credentials
}
); if (!response.ok()) {
throw new Error(
`Authentication failed with status ${response.status()}`
);
} const responseBody =
await response.json(); return respons
